title: “Great Location, Very Accomodating staff especially Jewel!”
text:

The vintage feel with modern decor makes this hotel unique, just don't stay in room 606 because of the sloping floors, good thing the front desk was kind enough to transfer us to another room the very first thing in the morning. They even gave me 2 rooms to choose from. 
Check out was a easy too.. We checked out at 12nn left our luggages at the concierge,had lunch and went back at the hotel lobby at 3PM our flight back home is at 8PM so they let me stayed in the lobby with my 1 year old son while waiting for our cab ride to the airport at 5PM. My son slept in the couch and it didn't bother them. 
Overall, we are very satisfied with our stay

title: “Great customer service; extremely clean rooms”
text:
Wonderful experience from the moment we walked in the lobby. Greeted warmly by bellhops, then reception personnel. Easy check-in with thorough information provided on available amenities. We weren't in the room 5 minutes until we heard a knock on the door -- turned out to be our housekeeper who wanted to say hello and give us two bottles of water.
Nice-sized suites with new appliances, plenty of coffee and tea, and clean upholstery/linens. When I did my usual bed-bug check, I noticed the pillow-top mattress and pads looked brand new.
Lots of families here, so a little noise in the halls, but not bad. Safe neighborhood. Looking forward to the complimentary breakfast buffet in the morning and manager's reception (drinks) tonight. Overall, very happy we chose this hotel over the Kimpton we wanted to book. Can't believe the room/amenities we got for such a great rate!

title: “Wish I could have rated it higher...”
text: Stayed here for business. When we first arrived...lots of construction going on outside the property. Check in was speedy & the front desk clerk was pleasant. Lobby was nice. I was put in an accessible room on the 2nd floor. So I had lots of space. Property is very clearly aged. Basic amenities in room. Shower was awesome...hot & great water pressure. It would have been nice to have lotion in the bathroom. Bed was ok. I liked that they had a microwave & fridge in the room. Flat screen TV with lots of channels. Nice selections for breakfast. Downfalls...older property, basic in room amenities, Internet moves at a snail's pace (that sucks when you're staying here for business), walls are thin (you can hear folks in adjoining rooms & all way). I love Marriotts...wish I could have rated this property higher.

title: “Clean, modern, quiet.. leave extra time for the elevators”
text:
Great experience at this hotel. Front desk staff very friendly and check in process painless. 
Small number of rooms per floor make it relatively quiet, as does the location (on Stone Street, not far from Wall Street but very little traffic through the night). Other hotels in the Financial District (Millenium Hilton, Marriott, etc) tend to be noisy due to ongoing construction at World Trade Center site. Am sensitive to noise and this hotel was very quiet. 
Room itself small, but not any smaller than usual New York rooms. Nice bathrooms with high end fixtures (also I noted an exhaust vent - unusual for a hotel but helpful to get the steam out!), bed was very comfortable. TV had a surprising number of HD channels. Air conditioning system was very noisy to start up (to the point I ended up turning it off as it was cycling on and off all night, waking me up each time). 
Disappointing that Hilton has chosen not to extend the usual "free wi-fi" courtesy that is normally found in the Doubletree family. While the business lounge offers free access, it would have been much more convenient had it been included in the room rate. 
The main reason this hotel only gets a 4 star is the terrible elevator service. It doesn't look it from the outside, but this is a 40+ story building, served by 3 elevators. I ended up taking the stairs a few times as got impatient with the elevator. 
Would certainly stay here again and recommend it to my colleagues.

title: “Good base for pre/post flight out of Seatac and exploring Seattle”
text:
My family and I only stayed one night as I had to pick my brother up from Seatac airport. Deciding to make it a nice outing we went to the zoo and then checked in at the hotel to end the night. Check in was quick and efficient, and the room was clean, contemporary in design and best of all, quiet when you consider the proximity to the airport. We had dinner at the restaurant and though the meal was brilliant we felt a bit out of place as we had our over tired infant with us. Good thing to keep in mind if you have little ones, it's best to eat outside of the hotel so you don't feel rushed or disturb the other diners' experience. The food is worthy of slowly savouring, and we tried our best to do so while keeping our son quiet/fed/entertained.
Don't forget to check out the hotel's "living room lounges" with its complimentary snacks and Haagen Daaz ice cream! The grounds around the hotel are great for a stroll and the scenery/landscaping are beautiful.
All in all, this hotel well exceeds the price you'd pay and is worthy of its high ranking on this site. I'd have rated it excellent instead of very good if only it had a bit more amenities (like a pool) but that's only because I'm trying to find "fault" with the property. It really is a wonderful hotel with great service and friendly staff.

title: “Needs attention soon”
text:
I bought a package at the United Nations property on LuxuryLink.com and was disappointed after having stayed at seven other LuxuryLink hotels. This extended stay facility isn't a true hotel and doesn't have the level of maintenance that a hotel would have. The floors are peeling, the drapes dirty, the linen rough and scratchy. It does have much more space and a kitchen that a hotel room wouldn't have. The decor is serviceable although getting a bit worn. For what I paid, I felt it was OK but if I'd paid their standard rates, I would have been quite upset.And the drunk guy singing in the halls one night didn't help! Security isn't sufficient to handle a situation like that.
Staff is friendly and tries but quite young and inexperienced. Housekeeping wasn't quick to clean when we requested it, the phone and the air conditioning weren't working properly in our unit.
All in all, I won't be back and others should be aware that this isn't up to a hotel standard.

title: “Good budget choice in expensive San Diego”
text: We stayed here after reading positive reviews and in general were quite pleased. We liked the older section with its minute room and shower, sort of had a 40s-50s vibe about it, and we asked for a room away from the highway so did not have issues with noise as some reviewers claimed. Top marks go to the always cheerful and cooperative staff; in fact, the owner should give them raises. Whatever they are making, it is not enough...their attitudes distinguish this motel from others in the same price range. Most impressive was the incredible cleanliness of everything, and it was obvious the cleaning staff took great pride in their work. Would make a few minor suggestions to the (responsive) owners, to upgrade the plain bar of soap and shampoo to a slightly higher brand, and to have the breakfast makers pay a little closer attention to the supply of food and utensils during the breakfast hours, perhaps checking every 10-15 minutes. But all in all, a good choice for budget accomodations in San Diego!

title: “Awesome hotel for a getaway weekend!”
text:
My husband and I stayed at XV Beacon last weekend and it was AWESOME! It is a beautiful hotel with a very courteous and friendly staff that we experienced throughout our entire stay. We loved the delicious treats upon arrival in our room, the stereo and the flat screen TV on the wall. The tasteful décor -a combination of old world, yet fashionably contemporary details made our stay very comfortable. We discovered a
warm and intimate feel about XV Beacon's rooms with a fireplace,
artwork and the detailed woodwork. The fresh flower in the room was a nice touch.
The Full Rain shower in the Bathroom was delightful and a perfect way to start the day! We also had a great Brunch in Mooo on Sunday morning- fresh ripe fruit, steamy hot cornbread and the Spinach and melted cheese Frittata was “to die for”. It was just a short walk to the Charles for a lovely stroll along the water on Sunday morning. I would highly recommend XV Beacon for a weekend getaway-luxurious and secluded, yet minutes from the bustling Back Bay and Faneuil Hall Marketplace.
It was a much needed respite from our hurried lifestyle.

title: “Very nice experience for a country boy going to town”
text: Being from a small town in Tennessee, I was very unsure of what to expect from the large city hotel. I was very surprised by the down home feel my wife and I received from the staff at the hotel from check-in to check-out. We were met by the doorman who graciously took care of our car and helped us check into our room. The young man at the desk did a great job of advising us on which tours to take and a great Italian restaurant in the West Loop neighborhood. Since we don't travel to large cities often we really appreciated the friendly atmosphere of the staff.........they always made us feel welcome and answered our questions easily and friendly. I would recommend this hotel to anyone wanting a pleasant experience free from the hustle and bustle of big city life, well located and within walking distance of everything. Thanks to all for a wonderful weekend.................we plan on returning.

title: “Nice historic building, beware partiers & thin walls”
text: Stayed for one night on college visit. Gorgeous old Federal Reserve building. Comfortable room, walked to major sites. Quiet part of town at night. Lobby filled with sounds from loud, drunken reception ... "frat" party in room next to ours lasted into the wee hours. Multiple visits by security didn't solve problem. Although our two calls to front desk were extremely polite, we never received a hint of an apology. MUST SEE: 5th floor historic photos of Fed and two gorgeous NC Wyeth murals of founding fathers and Lincoln pondering war finances (Wyeth Room at top of staircase). We aren't ones to go out of our way to see art, but these are VERY cool and well worth 5-10 min. before dinner or on your way out.

title: “Had a Great Time!!”
text:
My husband and I just returned from a 9 night stay at the Hilton Times Square. I researched alot of hotels prior to making our reservation. I chose this hotel because of the good reviews. For the most part everything that was said was true.
The location is right in the middle of everything! Convienent to anything and everything. Port Authority, subways, restaurants, Broadway shows and shops.
The rooms are larger that most and were very clean. The beds were extemely comforable and the bathroom was a decent size. We always had hot water. The elevators were fast. On 2 occasions we had to call maintenance, no sound on one tv channel and the a/c wasn't as cold as it could have been. The crew was very efficient and took care of the issues right away.
I cannot say enought about the staff. Everyone was extremely nice and helpful from the bellman to the front desk. Adrian the conciere was very pleasant and always willing to explain directions to us. Olga at the front desk was one of the nicest ladies I have ever met.
The only things I would change would be to add more drawer space and to have free internet service in your room. We paid over $500.00 a night and I thought it to be very unfair that I had to pay extra for this.
Other that that, we had a wonderful time and would return again.

title: “Great Customer Service”
text:
I have to post a comment here after my latest encounter with 'Rada' - staff @ the front desk. I've made 4 visits for business over the past year and stayed @ The Sheraton for 3 of them. Rada made a point of remembering my name after checkin on stay #1 and greeted me by name each time she saw me after that. On my trip to Indy last week, I was unable to get a room due to a convention, so had to book elsewhere. However, a coworker was checking in @ The Sheraton (at the end of my trip, so rooms were available again) and I walked into the lobby with him. Rada was at the desk and as soon as she saw me, she smiled and greeted me by name. The amazing thing is, the last time she saw me was April! She always goes out of her way to make me and my coworkers feel welcome, saying hello and greeting us by name. She's working in the right industry and The Sheraton should make sure they hold onto her.
The hotel is conveniently located, the beds are comfortable and the bar has decent food and the price was right for a stay downtown. Nothing fancy, but certainly clean and comfortable. There is a fitness room (small). The only problem I ran into was during a visit in early April. My room got a bit stuffy and I was unable to get AC (The hotel explained that due to the type of heating/cooling system they had, they could set it on heat OR cool - and based on the outside temp, it was on heat).
I would go back and would recommend this hotel.

title: “Fabulous hotel and location!”
text:
I am a frequent business traveler and stayed at the Fairmont Olympic 2 nights Feb 29 and Mar 1. The rooms were very big with a superbly comfortable bed. My view wasn't great, but I wasn't there for that (view of buildings across the way, no water from my room at least). The work desk was okay - not huge, but decent with one plug nearby. The room had an armchair with a little table as well, a minibar, coffee and such, a big closet with hooks and a small safe (in which I couldn't fit my big laptop). The bathroom was a big size with a separate room/door for shower and toilet. The toiletries were nice and there was a bathrobe, and a nice extra of two sets of slippers - that's very rare.
Room service was quick and good - I had a turkey club with fries and all was hot/cold where supposed to be; it came delivered on a rolling table instead of a tray, which I always think is a nice touch.
Everyone was extremely helpful - fast check-in, email my check-out folio, called a cab quickly, directed me on the walk to my business meeting, etc. Capitol Grille is right across the street for finer dining, and there seemed to be some places nearby for quicker and less expensive meals.
All in all, I thought it was a great hotel and I'd definitely stay there again.

title: “We'll be back!”
text: Just want to add one more "Excellent" rating to the list. Originally we were looking at budget hotels, but when we learned "budget hotel" in NYC means something a little different, we planned on spending a little more money on the hotel. We're very glad we did. We arrived hours before check-in not expecting to be given a room. They put us in a room with the king sized bed we requested, on the top floor (17th) of the hotel. I was concerned there would be noise from the service elevator our room was adjacent to, but heard nothing for the 2 days we were there - we felt like we were the only ones in the hotel! Room was immaculate, AC worked nicely and wasn't too loud, and the concierge helped us with getting transportation back to the airport. It was on a safe street, short walk to Times Square, subway, etc. We would definitely stay there again.

title: “Comfortable Stay”
text:
I won this hotel on a priceline bid so I had no real expectations to begin with. I was just hoping it was clean and comfortable. 
Arrived at 5pm on a Friday, no lines or problems checking in. Room was spacious and clean and had all the amenities I expected (shampoo, conditioner, soap, hair dryer, iron, safe). Room was on the hot side but opening the window and turning the thermostat down fixed that problem. I found the bathroom to be very clean with no signs of mold/mildew or peeling paint. The bed was a little lumpy but it's because of the futon style mattress they put on top of the regular mattress. Overall, we slept fine and didn't wake up with stiff backs or anything like that. 
I was a little worried after reading some of the other reviews but didn't experience any attitude from the staff. The other comments about the ridiculously overpriced food is correct...$40 for continential breakfast is accurate. I think the french toast was $28. Needless to say, we ate elsewhere! We did not use the pool, gym, fitness center or business center. We really only used the hotel to sleep in at the end of the day.
I would absolutely return to this hotel and would not hesitate to recommend it to our friends if we were sure they were only looking for a hotel. If they had special needs or reasons to book this particular hotel I couldn't really comment because we didn't use the other services. The doorman was fantastic when we checked out and helped us get a taxi and loaded our luggage in the back. I took some pictures of the room and will attach them. As i said, I would definitely return to this hotel.

title: “Fantastic place to stay”
text: This hotel would have been clean, stylish, and affordably priced in any part of DC, but to be so close to the White House and so many sites, it's a miracle! I booked a trip there to take my parents on a tour of the White House, and my mother was pre-knee replacement and needed only short distances on foot. I could not believe our luck at finding such a great rate on a room so close to everything we were visiting. The fact that there are 2 queens (not 2 doubles) in the double room made it possible for 3 adults to share one room comfortably. We had plenty of space in the room, which was something I was concerned about beforehand. The bathroom was large and impeccably clean. There was free wifi; a pleasant surprise as hotels of this caliber so often make guests pay. Because of mom's mobility issues, we used the valet several times, and the staff was extremely courteous and caring toward her needs. The staff in the hotel overal were outstanding and quick to help or offer advice on area restauratants. If you want to be close to the White House on a reasonable budget, then you can't find a better place.

title: “Nice hotel, but staff needs to learn manners”
text:
I was staying in this hotel for 1 night free of charge in room 740, the Bridal Suite, to make up for a bad experience at another Omni location earlier this year. The Suite was very spacious and had a great view of the garden from the terrace. The room was very clean and nicely laid out. The TV could definitely be bigger for such a large room, but not a big deal. The bathroom was also very clean and the shower/tub area was very spacious. We definitely loved the room.
You can tell by looking at the hotel and its finishings, that the hotel is old. It is nice and grand, but the age was showing. When we went to explore the pool area, the lady snapped at my wife asking for our room number. If she needs that information so we can just walk around the pool, she could have asked nicely. 
One big negative was parking - it costs $33 + tax to park here daily. We decided to go ahead and park here since our room was free of charge anyways. They told us to call down 5 minutes ahead of time when we needed our car. When we called down to get our car in the evening, there was no answer. We waited and called again 10 minutes later, no answer. We had to leave so we walked down and said we need our car immediately. Before I could even finish my sentence, the guy was telling me I should have called and I needed to wait. I didn't like his rude tone so I let him know it's his fault b/c no one was picking up the phone down there. The same thing happened AGAIN the next morning, and AGAIN he cut me off telling me I should have called ahead of time. He really pissed me off so I let him know he was being rude and didn't know what he was talking about.
Conclusion: Overall, this was a much better stay at an Omni for us. The hotel and room were very clean. But the interaction we had with the staff wasn't very good.

title: “Best Hampton Inn yet!”
text: I stayed at the Hampton Inn and Suites for two nights during a business trip and was thoroughly satisfied with this property. The staff is very friendly and attentive, and the rooms and facilities are modern and clean. The hotel is close to several good restaurants on or near the short north. Although the hotel does try to escape it's "Hampton" roots in several ways (e.g. expansive lobby, presidential suites, valet parking), the standard Hampton Inn products are present and accounted for: Hampton Inn bedding is comfy as usual, complimentary breakfast is standard Hampton menu, free internet access worked well. The hospitable staff was definitely a cut above Hampton standards, and in many ways were better than the staff at some very big Hilton hotels at which I've stayed. ! I'd definitely recommend this hotel to anyone traveling to Downtown Columbus.

title: “Small room, good location ...”
text:
I enjoyed a two-night stay on business at the Sheraton Four Points because the hotel was walking distance to most everything, including Metro Center station which is a key junction for the Metro underground. The White House and the national mall are roughly 4 blocks from the hotel as well.
Being there alone, the cramped room was acceptable because the beds were large enough and comfy. The bathroom seemed like it was made for people 4 feet and shorter. If I was there with my wife, we probably would have been stepping over one another and wishing for a hotel with more space.
There was noise from the street, hallway and the heating/cooling unit, but nothing out of the ordinary. The Internet was free, but not wireless. One end of the connection was partially broken, so I had to be careful not to bump it or I'd lose my connection. It wasn't a big deal, but hey, it's the little things that make up life and hotel stays.
Housekeeping was prompt, and the front desk staffers were polite. Nobody seemed to know how to direct me to the new Nationals baseball park, but then the hotel staff wasn't alone there. I leaped in a cab and said take me to the Nationals stadium, and the cabbie actually said "what's the intersection?" You're a D.C. cabbie and you don't know where ballpark is?! But I digress ...

title: “Great Free Breakfast”
text: I just got back from a night at the Residence Inn Phila. Center City. The location is great, within walking distance to the Liberty Bell, Independence Hall, the National Constitution Center, The Gallery, The Reading Terminal Market, and lots more. The only parking is valet, and it's not cheap, but it was convenient and our car was delivered in a timely manner. The staff were all very friendly. The included full hot breakfast was lovely. There was anything you can imagine to eat. You can cook your own hot waffles, there were prepared breakfast sandwiches, prepared yogurt parfaits, plus eggs, sausage, hot and cold cereal, 3 different juices, coffee, tea, etc. I could go on and on - it was quite a nice breakfast in a beautiful room. They thought of everything - there was even whipped cream for the waffles. The room we had was a suite with a separate bedroom, living area, and fully equipped kitchen. The room seemed older and had old style tv's in both the bedroom and the living room. The bathroom was comfy and the bed was soft, with a couple different types of pillows. I can't stress how helpful and nice the staff was. I would stay here again.

title: “Perfect in every way!!!”
text:
Great location. The perfect location to see NYC. Very quiet at the weekend. Open top tour bus is the best way to travel because of value for money. City Sights NY was perfect. There is a bus stop a stone's throw from the hotel and the tube is one street up. 
The hotel breakfast didn't look great so we just ate out around. This wasn't a problem though as there are tons of yummy diners and cafes nearby. A&F is only down the road and tons of lovely restaurants too in a cobled street waterside area. Feels very european and classy (a nice contract from the brashness of time square).
The breakfast was the only disappointing thing about the hotel and we didn't eat it (may have been better than it looked). I would recommend going room only though. The prices are incredible, given the size of the room and quality of the hotel. Very stylish and boutique feel.
We were upgraded. It was my friends 30th. We stayed in room 805. Surely the best room in the hotel. As big as my sitting room and lounge put together!! I though NYC rooms were sposed to be small?!!!!?? Two massive double beds, a leather couch, a desk area. 
Bathroom didn't really match up with the 5 star standard of the room but it was pleasant and clean and well appointed.
Staff were friendly but left you to be independant. Perfect! Free internet and computer = a definate plus. 
We booked through Late rooms and paid 100-150 pounds a night. 50-70 each. What a bargain!!!
I would definately go back to Eurostars when in NYC. I don't even think the big hotels (where you pay 4 times as much) would come close to comparing in value for money, location and style.
Book this now or you'll regret it. Prices are jumping up week after week.

title: “The good, the bad and the ugly.”
text:
The Good~room was larger than expected, free internet in room.
The Bad~one of the queen beds was like sleeping on a roller coaster, apparently the frame was loose and every time you moved the whole bed did too. Carpet was stained. Bathtub drained very slow. T.V. ~ poor choice of channels and reception was bad. No exhaust fan in bathroom. Housekeeping sprinkled carpet fresh around the room but forgot to vacuum it up. The whole room smelled like a funeral parlor.
The Ugly~I forgot my camera in the Tugs Resaurant at the table. I went back to look for it but it mysteriously disappeared. By the way there was only one other couple there, seated at the far end of the room and only one waitress. I called the next day and got the run around from everyone. I requested to speak to a manager and was told that since it was a holiday weekend no manager was on duty. I made another call the following day and requested to speak to a manager, got connected to voice mail and have yet (five hours later) to receive a return call.

title: “Decent Stay”
text:
I think this hotel is ok for business travelers. I would not recommend it for families on vacation. The location is in an industrial area. There are two parking levels with their own entrance. Both parking lots are small. For some reason, many of the cars took up two spaces. As a result, there wasn't enough parking spaces. Be careful if the lot is full; the best way to exit is backing out all the way to the street.
The staff is friendly and the room is nice. The air conditioner is a bit noisy and it can get a little chilly even at the lowest setting. The swimming pool was not very clean, so we decided not to use it. The breakfast was very good. I probably would not come back though.

title: “$250 (prepaid) got me a sofa bed and a bad attitude from the staff”
text: I was in town for business and had chosen the Hyatt because all of the good hotels in Center City were full. I prepaid for my hotel room a week and a half in advance to hold it for late arrival, but when I arrived, I was sent to a hospitality suite with only a sofa bed. The brand-new alarm clock on the bar- with the "12:00" sticker still on it- was also a particuarly classy touch. Not only had the front desk employee not told me that I was being sent to such a room, but she ignored me when I called down to complain. Twenty minutes later, the night concierge told me that this happens often, since the Hyatt apparently overbooks its guest rooms fairly frequently, and that my (furious) reaction to my "guest room" was typical. I would have expected such policies and customer service of a Motel 6, not a Hyatt Regency.

title: “Very nicely done.”
text: We met friends in Philadelphia, and stayed here for 3 nights. Our room had 2 double beds, and was quite large and comfortable, with a bay window looking out over the city. Our friends had one king sized bed and said that their room was quite small. The hotel was first built around 1900, as an in-town spot for the wealthy to stay. It retains a lot of the features of that era, with mosaic tile floors and vintage woodwork. We felt it was extremely well-run and well-appointed. The bathrooms are small, as you would expect, but you have everything you need. A cold breakfast was served until 10:30, with hard-boiled eggs, cereals, lovely pastries, coffe, tea and juices. The staff, especially the General Manager, John, were very personable and helpful. The hotel is located at 12th and Spruce, a short walk to Market Street where you can pick up tour buses or the Pflash trolley that makes a continuous loop around the city. The historic district is about 6-7 blocks east. If you don't want to walk, taxis are plentiful and fairly cheap. There are many very good restaurants in the area, and the staff is eager to recommend their favorites. We were very pleased with this hotel. It's upscale but casual and friendly. To us, they hit all the right notes. We will definitely stay there on our next trip.

title: “Good times in NYC”
text:
We chose this place based upon online reviews and price. We were a little concerned because it was quite cheap in comparison to the competition, but were pleasantly surprised.
The place is well located on the Upper West Side, close to Central Park and the subway, so getting in and out of downtown is easy. The staff are very friendly and are happy to provide assistance or give advice if needed. The reservation was correct, which is even better.
The stairs are slow, but that's no problem because the stairs are available. The only other problem is that there is no to dry one's hands in the bathroom - you have to go back to your room or remember to take a towel with you - hand dryers would go a long way.
Ultimately, if you're looking for a very basic room in a good location, I'd recommend this place. Good location, good basic rooms, friendly staff, what more could you ask for?

title: “Highly Recommended!”
text: We stayed in the Excelsior Hotel in New York from July 20-22, 2005. This was our first time staying at the Excelsior--we will definitely stay there in the future. We paid $175 per night plus tax (came to a little over $200 per night with everything) for two people (queen bed)--booked the room through Orbitz. We felt like this was a reasonable price for the quality of the room (in New York). We were very pleased with the condition of the room (especially the bathroom)--extraordinarily clean!, and the decor was very pleasant as well. The room was not especially large but was not cramped or uncomfortably small--the hotel rooms I have had in New York over the years tend to be on the smaller side, so I have come to expect this. The weather was extremely hot when we were in NY, and thank goodness, the AC in the room worked very well. The bed was quite comfortable. I was concerned about how the staff would be at the hotel after reading other reviews here, but they were basically fine--not especially friendly, but they were certainly professional--we had no problems with them or with our room. The breakfast options at the hotel were expensive, so we ate breakfast at the Manhattan Diner over on Broadway (on 76th, I think)--it is excellent and very reasonably priced. There are many very good and reasonable restaurants within just a few blocks of the hotel, another added bonus. Wireless internet access in the hotel is available for a fee (we paid $25 for three days of access, which seemed okay)--it worked perfectly. The location (West 81st Street near Columbus Avenue) is very convenient to Upper West Side attractions, including the Museum of Natural History (across the street from the hotel), and also Central Park, which is also right there. We were not bothered by traffic (or other) noise in our room. Overall, we thoroughly enjoyed staying at the Excelsior, and we highly recommend it!

title: “value with a view”
text: spent the weekend at this hotel in conjunction with the nyc half-marathon. we like staying in lower manhattan for the history, great restaurants, playgrounds for our daughter, safe places to run,and relative value when considering nyc prices. when we checked in, it was quite late, and the staff seemed pretty annoyed. that made me wonder what we got ourselves into. nevertheless, the room we requested was ready with additional pillows as requested. we asked if we could buy a few water bottles anywhere, and the girl checking us in said she'd send up some water, on the house, which was very nice. the views from our junior suite on the 26th floor were spectacular!!!! we enjoyed the view at night, and during the day. the suite had plenty of room for the three of us with a king bed and a pull out sofa. swimming pool was really nice, if a bit cold, and our daughter enjoyed herself a great deal. noise from the wtc site was an issue the first night, but was nonexistent the second night. overall, we would stay here again for the location, views and value.

title: “Ok for kids, not worth the price.”
text:
To start off the staff were great, always saying hello and offering a smile. The hotel itself needs work. 
Upon entering our room 3707 I noticed a what looked to be blood stain on the sheets after pulling them back, then I noticed mold in the shower. Really, Mold? I also didn't care for the hotels policy on changing of sheets and towels, you have to call and tell them you want new sheets. I much prefer the Hilton policy of leaving the card on the bed if you are happy with keeping the sheets. Don't make me go out of my way for something so simple. During our three night stay the cleaning staff never replenished the bath soaps, only the toothpaste, which was a nice touch. The first night our connected room neighbors decided to start yelling around 3am, you could hear straight through the doors. I called security and they took care of it promptly. You can also hear straight through the door leading to the hallway. How do hotels not get this right? 
We spent much of our time at the adult pool, which was the perfect temperature and had a wonderful hot tub with waterfall. They did a great job secluding the pool from the activity pool, didn't hear a peep from the other pool, just the sound of waterfalls. The chairs by the pool were very nice and there were plenty. The pool could have used a midday cleaning of leaves that fall from the many trees surrounding the pool. Finally, I would appreciate staff enforcing the no kids in the adult pool. Their was a family with kids jumping and splashing around the Adult pool for a couple hours and the staff didn't take notice. I shouldn't have to bring to attention or enforce the rules of the pool.
In closing for almost $400 (w/taxes & $23 resort fee) a night I expected much more. (Those are Ritz and Four Seasons prices.)

title: “Noisy!!”
text: Just returned from a one night stay at the Algonquin. The history of the hotel makes it worth a visit, but don't expect much more. There is a hotel being built right behind it and the noise from the construction equipment digging all day long is enough to drive you crazy. The rooms are small, but sweetly decorated, The plumbing as you might imagine is very old and the fixtures are meant to give that "old fashioned" look, There is no luxury to the bathroom at all. The bed was super comfortable and the linens were great quality. The elevators were painfully slow and cramped. You must posess patience to stay here. The location however is excellent, close to all. If you catch a great deal and won't be in the room too too much, then try the Algonquin.

title: “Great city break”
text:
We've just returned from a 5 day break in Washington. Arrival at the airport was so smooth alot easier than New York. We had to find our own way to the hotel, before we left we got some quotes on line to be picked up and dropped back, don't be tempted, we never actually got around to accepting the quotes, but trust me that was the best choice, You are about 45mins from Washington, depending on the traffic and it cost us $70 one way, the quote we were getting back, they were to return aswell but they were coming in $250 and up, total rip-off, booking the taxi back was even easier the hotel did it for us the night before and that was another $70, so was really pleased.
Getting around Washington is either on foot, most of the sites are in walking distance of each other, or you could be brave like we were and use the metro, abit confusing at first but soon got the hang of it, you buy a travel card for as little as $10 from the machine and you keep adding to it, i think we put about $40 each and we never spent a penny on a taxi, 5 coloured train lines on the map, each is very detailed, so you can soon work out were you need to get off.
The hotel is in a great spot, close to the metro lines and easy walking to the White House and all the monuments, there is a Starbucks connected to the left of the hotel, great for breakfast and there is a restaurant and bar connected to the right, the food quality is great and not over priced.
The staff are really helpful, infact we booked our trips through the hotel,couldn't have been easier.We booked a king size room which was great, big enough for what we needed, all the essentials were there, safe, iron, hairdryer, typical city break hotel. As we didnt need to leave the hotel till 14.30 we asked if we could keep the room a little longer which was no problem
The thing we did notice unlike the other American cities there aren't alot of fast food places to eat, we only saw 2 macdonalds. We found a nice restaurant down by the Old Post Office Building, called the Elephant and Castle, nicest proper burger we've had for a long time, and the staff are really friendly.
The city itself is really clean and you do feel safe walking round. All of the non-private muesums are free of charge to get in, but you do need to get there by a reasonable time as you are given allocated times to view certain things, we went to the holocaust muesum, we got there about 11.00am and we could view the main part of it at 1pm, but there are plenty of other things to see while you are waiting, you think this is abit of a pain when they give you your time but it does stop it getting packed in there so you see alot more.

title: “Great location”
text:
I stayed at the Affinia for a week - and loved it. I had used Trip Advisor to help find a good hotel in New York and was not disappointed. I styed in a huge room with the biggest bed I have ever seen. My parents (in 60s) had another room with two huge Queen beds. Both rooms had great views of Manhattan (26th and 28th floors). We used the kitchens in the rooms for breakfasts. It was great having a huge fridge to keep drinks cold. 
The rooms were spotless - best maid service ever. There are three lifts which you never wait more than a minute for (a bonus in such a big hotel). The staff were incredibly friendly and helpful. There is an added bonus of an air-conditioned gym which residents can use 24 hours a day for free. It is quite big - with great views. You can also hire CD players, weights and yoga mats for free.
The location of this hotel could not be bettered. The subway is a block away. Times Sq is just 20 minutes away, the Empire State less than five. There are dozens of bars and restaurants nearby (try Sarges for a real US dining treat) and Kimi for fab Japanese food. The Barking Dog (next to hotel) does great buttermilk pancakes, but beware service is slow and it can lack atmosphere.
I plan to stay at this hotel again when I am next in the city. It really is good value for New York with rooms much bigger than many more expensive hotels in Manhattan.

title: “Great location - great vibe”
text:
Let me preface by stating that this was my first trip to San Diego (w/ wife - both in our 30s/no kids) and stayed for a week.
It's hard to separate the Hard Rock Hotel in San Diego from the neighborhood it is in: Gaslamp. The hotel basically anchors the entrance to the Gaslamp District (comprised of hotels, restaurants, bars and shops too numerous to mention) and reflects the general atmosphere. On the weekends, HRH is a party place - period. It is loud, crowded and energentic. During the week, it is laidback and has a lot of contemporary charm.
My wife and I used the weekends to let loose and the weekdays to move about the city for some sightseeing; it worked perfectly at the HRH. Being a registered guest at the hotel gets you on a pseudo-VIP list to the hotel's clubs on Friday/Saturday and to the Sunday Invervention pool party on Sunday afternoon. These events are very pretentious but fun (probably more so with a group of friends). For sightseeing, the location at the "foot" of the Gaslamp District is perfect. Not only is Petco Park right next door, 2 very user-friendly city MTS trolleys are within walking distance. Knowing what I know now, I could easily get to every major sightseeing destination in San Diego using the trolley system and the 2 major sightseeing transportation companies (one is a trolley/other is a double-decker bus) without a car.
As for general hotel service/amenities, HRH follows the general trend I felt in the city itself: a) service is average and nobody really puts forth much extra effort and b) prices are on the expensive side. We did appreciate our housekeeping crew - their customer service was the best of any we received in San Diego (including all restaurants, bars, tours, etc...). The room itself was a bit odd though. We had a King Suite (with a great balcony). However, the layout of the room is not very practical and the fact that the bathroom had sort of an "open air" concept will be off-putting to some. Finally, valet parking in too high at $30 per day but seems to be competitive with the area.
I would definitely stay at HRH again and would suggest it to friends. However, it is not for everyone. The place is, again, full of energy (i.e. noisy, young crowd) and not concerned about making you feel at home (on purpose, I would assume) as some hotels do. I think if people understand what the place is about before going, the experience will be a positive one.

title: “Know what you are in for”
text:
Yes this hotel is close to the airport and certainly cheap. And there is the free shuttle to the airport. So for early morning flights it is better than fighting the LA traffic. 
But as single women travelling this is not in a good location and all the rooms are open access with no security. They offer 1/2 day rates. The staff was very friendly but we could not get rooms near each other, nor could we get rooms on the first floor and we had lots of luggage that we had to haul up the stairs. Our rooms were at the back of the hotel and looked out to a housing complex. They smelled terrible and were not very nice - but it is a Travelodge and you get what you get. There are no options for eating other than Denny's. We actually ended up staying in a room together because of the security concern.

title: “Really wanted to love it, but didn't ...”
text:
My husband, new baby and I stayed here 10 years ago and loved this artsy, elegant hotel. We were delighted to have the opportunity to return, now with our five children. Perhaps my sentimental expectations were too high, but we were profoundly disappointed. 
 We had a an executive suite connecting to a double/double ($700 plus per night pre-tax) PLUS another double/double for our nanny (ANOTHER $320ish per night pre-tax) The service was terrible, with one little thing snowballing into the next and here they are:
First, the hotel is on a busy downtown street with no pull-off area to unload a vehicle, I had to run inside to track down the valet during Seattle rush hour while my hubby and remaining family got honked at while idling in front of the hotel. Once in our rooms, the valet didn't bother to ask which bag went where -- just unloaded them all in the living room area. (i redirected). I asked abour our crib. He didn't know if there were cribs. He didn't know if the hotel had mini fridges available either . He said he would ask. He never did, so I tracked down the cribs. I was told by the front desk there were no mini fridges (i doubt this is true).
We had two bath towels in each bathroom for a family of 7. I did get more 45 minutes after my request.
The rooms have floor to ceiling windows. They are elegant and attractive. They are not practical. There is no closet or chest of drawers in the exec. suite bedroom (it's in the living area). The bed -- while comfortable -- takes up most of the room. There is only very limited counter space in the bathroom. It is an older tub shower.
The worst was our second floor location directly above busy First Street. The first night (a Sat.) was unbearable. We couldn't sleep but the front desk said it would be better the second night (a Sun) as there had been a parade and festival downtown on Sat. The front desk manager said she'd look around for other available rooms, but never bothered to call back. Despite mostly great reviews on TA, the most frequent negative was the noise which most reviewers assigned to passing garbage trucks. I was told via email in advance of our trip that our room requirements left the hotel with no choice but 2nd floor (lowest floor) rooms for us. But I was also told the garbage trucks had been rescheduled and this was no longer a hotel problem. Nonetheless, at 3 or 4 a.m. both nights we heard something that sounded like a garbage truck! I did not get out of bed to verify. On day 2, I asked for fans which helped drown out the noise on night two.
As we essentially had a 2-bedroom suite, there were three different TVs. All used different operating systems (lodgenet, etc.) so what was available on one was not necessarily available on the other. The maintenance man, originally summoned to fix the broken AC in one room, confirmed the other TVs weren't broken. He did not know why they were on different systems.
On Sunday morning at 8:30, I went to the lobby for some of the highly-touted iced coffee. It is promoted everywhere as being offered until 10 a.m. on the weekends, including on a sign on the table where the coffee is served. The pitcher was empty. I asked at the front desk and was told there wasn't any more. I said you can't run out of iced coffee unless you've run out of coffee, which is impossible in Seattle. She insisted they were, so I asked to see the manager on duty. After a punitive 10-minute wait, the m.o.d. came out and said it meant they would have to brew more then ice it down (yes! this is the complex recipe for iced coffee). She said it could take several minutes. I told her we'd be in the hotel restaurant. About 20 minutes later, she did bring it to me. We also had 4 $20 restaurant vouchers for b'fast as part of our package. I asked if we could use them for room service instead to spare the other guests the agony of dining next to our boisterous clan of 8. We were told no, which is how we ended up in the restaurant served by a cheerless waitress who brought GLASSES of ice water to everyone , including our one year old and two year olds in high chairs. When we asked her to take them away so the kids didn't knock them over, she knocked one over herself, getting the table and two people wet. No apology, but at least she gave herself an 18 percent tip for our "convenience."
The hotel's listed amenities include turndown service at night and a newspaper in the morning. We received neither. When I mentioned this at check out, the woman behind the desk said "you have to request those." How would one know to do this?
The only "break" i caught was when I ran out of milk for our baby after 6 p.m. which is when Seattle rolls up the carpet for the night. The Bookstore Bar bartender had mercy on me and filled up my 4oz sippy cup gratis. BTW, it is a beautiful, cozy, warm and charming bar. If I were traveling with my spouse only, we definitely would have had a drink or two there.
On the plus side, the hotel is convenient to Pike's Place. It does have a great bar. The beds are comfy. As I learned from other TA reviewers, you do get a $10 minibar credit and free wifi if you join kimpton in touch, which we did. You can check facebook for a password that will get you another perk. In July, it was "flip flops" which got us either two glasses of wine or a movie. No time for either but our tots enjoyed two half hour episodes of "Dora the Explorer," which otherwise would have cost us $2.99 each (seriously).

title: “Cannot recommend this hotel enough!”
text:
This hotel is fantastic! I cannot rave about it enough.
This is a two star hotel so this review is not aimed at those used to staying at the Plaza or the 4Seasons. We are a young couple on an extended trip looking for a hotel in SanFrancisco in a good location for a fair price. The Comfort Inn by the Bay ticks all the boxes.
The room was clean, spacious with good cable tv, in-room safe, refrigerator, free wireless internet and free local calls. Each morning we could walk to Fisherman's Wharf to ride the cable-car (4 blocks-not uphill!). There is also good bus links from right outside including the buses to Market Street and Fisherman's wharf. The area is safe. Lombard Street is quite a busy road and the traffic could be heard at times but it didn't bother us too much. The front desk were not super enthusiastic but helped us with bus links and a chinese takeaway (after a long drive from Yosemite!).
We were going to stay at a 3 star hotel for $185 but saw that this 2star hotel offered a view of the bay for $20 less so we decided to go for it. The attached photo of the Golden Gate Bridge was taken from our room. The view was excellent. We were so happy we decided to stay at the Comfort Inn and for anyone considering a stay here it is well worth the extra $20 for the bay view room. 
I would definately stay here again and it would probably be my first choice hotel, even if we are not on a budget! There is so much to do in fabulous SanFrancisco that you only need to be in the room to sleep!

title: “Great rooms, very clean”
text: We stayed at the Hyatt on May 5-8, 2007. I booked the hotel directly on the 800#, used the discount code from the SACVB website. This rate beat any I found on the internet. The room was 2 doubles, standard. Very roomy, clean. We were on the 5th floor and our room overlooked the Alamo. The pool on the roof offered wonderful day and night views of the city. They have a wonderful gym and hot tub on the roof. The Hyatt is right in the middle of the action, we walked everywhere on the Riverwalk. Valet parking is the way to go at the Hyatt. Parking is expensive everywhere in San Antonio, so be prepared. Breakfast in the hotel restaruarnt is expensive- 16.95 for the buffet, but includes all food and drink. Children and Seniors are offered a discount rate. We had "brunch" at the buffett every morning and saved up for dinner at the Riverwalk restarurants. Quite a pleasant stay.

title: “This place is run down, not taken care of at all”
text: This hotel is a great old building (formerly the Paso Del Norte in the old days), the Westin chain remodeled the place about 20 years ago and made this gem gorgeous. The Camino Real chain bought the hotel from the Westin Chain and has let the hotel deteriorate over the past 10 years. It is unfortunate because the rooms are big but the Camino Real chain has spent zero money on upkeep. The furniture and rooms are very dated, the plumbing fixtures look old and our room heat did not work at all. When I checked in, other guests were complaining about service and problems. The Camino Real was once a great hotel chain, but the Mexican owners take zero pride in keeping things up. We stayed here only due to location but I doubt I will stay again. Location for the Plaza theater is good but other than that, this place is living off of past glory. The owners obviously just do not care what anyone thinks. It is a pity the buffoons who own this place dont take more pride in the place!

title: “Thumbs up for Hotel Staff / Two Big Thumbs WAY DOWN for Bar Staff”
text:
OK, we all lnow how one's customer service experience can often make the biggest impression on how much you enjoy a hotel stay. And how many have you have ever stayed at a hotel where the actions/attitude of one or a few individuals just totally ruins your experience at a hotel - well the latter was our experience at the Hotel Havana. 
First my background - my wife and I currently live in Austin and we are very familiar with Liz Lambert's two hotels here. I also travel quite extensively throughout the Americas, Europe and Asia. 
IMO, the Hotel Havana is trying to differentiate itself from the hotel competition in San Antonio, which quite frankly is easy to do. Aren't many SA hotels going for the shabby chic minimalist look.
Hotel staff as mentioned by other reviewers are personable and professional. We liked that the hotel location is removed from the Riverwalk "action" ( full disclosure - not a fan of the downtown Riverwalk area).
Now for the big thumbs down: early Friday night around 9:30PM, my wife and I walk into the downstairs Hotel Havana bar. The place is small and all 4 seats at the bar are occupied as are most of the couches and loungers. There are a few unoccupied single chairs that do not look very comfortable and we also see a grouping of 8 lounger chairs and sofas unoccupied and decide to sit down amongst them. We notice the ubiquitous "reserved" sign on one of the tables. Immediatley one of the waitresses walks up to us and the first words out of her mouth is that these seats are reserved and we "have to leave". I calmly asked her if she knew when her "guests" were scheduled to arrive. She did not know but said that the seats were reserved for a large group (!) and we "could not sit there". I responded that we were paying guests in the hotel, we only wanted one glass of wine and if in fact the "reservees" were to appear while we still had unfinished wine in our glass, that we would graciously step away and finish our wine elsewhere in the bar. This was quickly rejected by our unfriendly waitress as heresy and with a "you will have to speak to the manager".
5 minutes passed by, no manager and no wine. I walked up to the bar, same unfriendly and unapolgetic waitress and order 2 glasses of wine from her. Watched carefully to ensure only wine was poured into the glasses. I walked back to the "reserved" seats with the glasses of wine and within seconds we are confronted with "I am the manager, you CAN'T sit here and you HAVE to leave". I again mentioned that I was guest at the hotel and reiterated my proposal - sit here, enjoy my wine and leave the moment his reservees show up. This was summarily rejected by said manager - I could have been demanding an increase in state income taxes as far as he was concerned. Now, I have enjoyed a cocktail or two at several LA, NY, Las Vegas, Miami better drinking establishments, so I am familiar with "bar attitude" but I really had my doubts that JayZ and Beyonce were about to walk into Hotel Havana ordering cases of Crystal.
The manager was extremely demanding that we vacate the reserved seats immediately. Admittedly it devolved into a confrontational discussion and we eventually decided to move seats. Clearly this manager had not passed "Avoiding Confrontational Customer Interactions" 101 courses at Bar Management School.
We took 15 minutes to finish our wine and left. And.....those reserved seats.....still unoccupied as we walked out.
Not to worry Mr. Bar Manager......we won't add any wear and tear to your precious bar furniture in the future.
So to the Bar Manager and bar staff at the Havana bar.....a big thumbs down and a recommendation to read a classic book "How to Win Friends and Influence People".....and if you want to play pretend we're an LA/NY/Miami bar......first you have to wear black and try to find some remotely justifiable reason to cop an attitude.

title: “Great experience”
text: Over my recent weekend trip to Boston, my girlfriend and I chose to stay at the Charlemark Hotel, which is a boutique hotel located in a great spot on Boylston st. From the modern ammenities to the extremely helpful staff, we found our stay to be more enjoyable than at many of large hotel chains that we are used to. They made you feel as though the services they offered were entirely focused on you. The newly renovated lounge and lobby area gives off an incredibly upscale vibe and is a great place to people watch. Rumor has it Tom Brady, quarterback of the Patriots, has been seen at the martini bar there. The rooms are modest size but are equiped very nicely. We stayed in the basement which we found to be a pleasant surprise. It is extremely quiet and you're guaranteed a great night of sleep. The room was great, from the surround sound stereo to the large flat screen tv and modern bath. When staying there ask for Kyle, the operations manager, and he'll ensure a great stay and recommend all the best hotspots in Boston. I would definately stay at the Charlesmark in the future

title: “Arquitectura neoyorkina y buen servicio”

title: “Great view from the top”
text: My husband and I wanted to stay in Seattle for a couple of days after our cruise to Alaska. Since we only had a couple of days, we wanted something close to the popular attractions in Seattle, i.e. Space Needle. This place turned out to be an excellent value. It's not too expensive and you can walk to the Space Needle. It was also easy to jump on the monorail and go downtown, Pike's Market, and the aquarium. The room was comfortable and clean. There's no air conditioning but since the high temperature was about 70 degrees, it didn't matter plus you can open the windows. We loved that there was a Starbucks attached to the lobby. The best thing was the rooftop deck where you can just sit in the chairs and enjoy a spectacular view of Seattle.

title: “Loved the Hotel Commonwealth”
text: Stayed at the Hotel Commonwealth for one night in April, 2004. Quite impressed. Room was large and beautiful with so many amenities. I had stayed at the Westin Copley Sq the evening before and even their "heavenly" beds did not compare to the comfort of the beds at the Hotel Commonwealth. The linens were first class and amazingly soft. The staff was gracious and helpful. The room was clean and new. While it is about a 20 minute walk to the "rest" of Boston, there is a subway stop right out front as well. Also, the 20 minute walk is down beautiful Commonwealth avenue, so it is not a hardship in the least. Prices were reasonable for the Boston area, with parking included in my package. Note that traffic gets heavy around the hotel when there are games at Fenway and you may have to work around that in your departure times. All in all, a small hotel to rival the large chains...a "secret" that eventually won't be so secret.

title: “Avoid the Blackstone 1 King/2 Queens "Bait & Switch"”
text:
My wife and kids and I had a very disappointing experience at the Blackstone this past weekend. I had booked two rooms for two nights at the Blackstone 6 months ago for Lollapalooza this year, and it turned out to be a very poor choice. When I had tried to book the rooms on the Blackstone's website, it would only let me book rooms described as "1 King or 2 Queen." Because my wife and I were traveling with four teenagers, I called the Blackstone's reservation number to make the reservation instead of doing it on-line so that I could confirm that I would be able to get 2 rooms with 2 beds in each room. Given that I was booking the rooms so early, I was assured by the person taking the reservation that this wouldn't be a problem. However, when we got to the hotel, we were told that there were no "double queen" bed rooms available. Obviously, we wouldn't have booked the Blackstone hotel if I had known this would be the case, and we weren't alone in this experience. The couple checking in next to us was told the same thing and had the same problem. 
The Blackstone clearly knows how many King bedrooms and double Queen bedrooms that it has when it takes reservations. This "1 King or 2 Queen beds" option was simply a "bait and switch" scam by the Blackstone. Don't be fooled by this like we were. 
To make matters worse, from the time we checked in, it took 3 calls and 6 hours for the hotel to bring up 2 roll-away beds. And then to cap off our less-than-stellar Blackstone experience, there was urine still in the toilet in one of the rooms that we checked into on Friday. While this didn't ruin our experience, it certainly wasn't pleasant.
The Blackstone is a very nicely decorated hotel, and the rooms are very comfortable. From the stand point of the rooms, they were fine. However, at this point, I can't imagine recommending the Blackstone to anyone staying in Chicago. If you want to experience downtown Chicago, stay at the Affinia. My wife and I have stayed there several times, and it is excellent. And if you're coming down to Lollapalooza next year, I'd suggest staying at the Hilton or perhaps even the Travelodge. They are both just as close to Grant Park, and if you make a reservation, you will know what you're getting.

title: “Great Choice For Pacific Beach”
text:
Tower 23 is a chic, upscale hotel, located on the boardwalk, in the heart of Pacfic Beach. The hotel features 44 spacious, well-equipped rooms/suites and a restaurant with full bar. The Tower Deck, located on the 2nd floor and overlooking the boardwalk, is a great place to take in the ocean view and enjoy your favorite cocktail. Guest services/amenities include concierge, business services, in-room dining and movies, morning newspaper, valet parking, laundry service and complimentary "Wi-Fi" internet. Tower 23 does not have a swimming pool.
We stayed in a "Surf Pad"; a very nice, ocean-front room with balcony. The spacious room featured a large Serenity bed, wall-mounted, flat screen HD-TV, X-Box entertainment center, cordless telephones, safe, iron and board. The bathroom featured a step-in shower (no bath tub), a hair dryer and quality bath robes.
JRDN is the on-site restaurant, featuring steaks, seafood and sushi. JRDN offers inside and patio dining and is complimented by a full-service bar that gets quite lively at night. We dined at JRDN one evening; the food was very good, albeit expensive. I enjoyed one of the best steaks I ever had and my wife raved about the Ahi tuna. JRDN provides in-room dining for breakfast, lunch, dinner and mid-night snacks. We ordered in-room for breakfast each day of our stay; again finding the food to be very good.
Service at Tower 23 was excellent and the friendliness of all staff members we had contact with was notable. Located just north of Crystal Pier, Tower 23 is within walking distance to countless restaurants, bars and shops.
We are local San Diego County residents, who have stayed at many of the better hotels in Pacific Beach; including Pacific Terrace, Ocean Park Inn and Capri By The Sea. We thoroughly enjoyed our 4-night stay at Tower 23 and look forward to a return visit.
If you have any questions or would like to view additional photos of the hotel, feel free to contact me through the Trip Advisor message system.

title: “Don't do it!!!”
text:
This hotel is a tip, could've cried when we got to our room after a hours wait in a queue to check in, the bathroom smelt of urine (had got under the flooring) there was a hole in the bath, the bath had been painted in what looked like gloss paint! The carpets were sticky and dirty, the paintwork was all peelong and had never been rubbed down just painted over and over, over the years, you could cup your hands and run along the skirting coming up with handfuls of accumulated filth. The Air-Con was hanging off the wall and made a banging sound 24/7 The furniture was from the 1970's the bed was as hard as nails, but overall the place was filthy, we changed rooms and the second one was just the same. we rung around other hotels but as it was 4th of July week everything was booked, so we were stuck!!
I always thought the Americans were picky, but they did not seem to mind the squalour of this place, although it is centrally located, close to all sightseeing and attractions I would not recommend it to anyone, I'm not posh by any means, but this place was squalid, you had to wear shoes in the rooms as the floors were sticky, don't even look under or behind the beds, you'd be sick, they smelt horrid damp and of urine, the bedlinnen had cigarette burns in it. 
Dont be fooled by the website pictures, the rooms are nothing like it shows, when we complaine dthey did not bat an eyelid and told us all the rooms were the same and if we wanted to check out we'd get a full refund off our holiday company, you could tell they dealt with these complaints all the time, I took 100's of photo's of New York but not one of the interior of this hotel as it was so disgusting and such a let down. I travelled there with my Niece as a surprise for her 16th Birthday and this place was absymal and such a let down to what was supposed to be a great week. I would never stay there again.

title: “Lustre is tarnished”
text: 4th annual trip and stay here: rooms, property, views & staff certainly remain wonderful. We made reservations 1+ month ago and when medical situation (surgery) came up we were told our payment was "non-refundable." So, we made to trip: at check-in we were informed that the room type we'd paid for was unavailable, but an upgrade to a suite was = another $100 per night. The suite was very nice, but a couple of features were broken & looked at by staff, but not repaired while we were there (3-nights). Even though we had purchased a stay-two-nights & get 3rd night free package it apparently didn't include the "upgrade" which we learned at check-out. What a scam! A fifth stay here is very doubtful at present.

title: “Good luck getting there--and FORGET IT if you think it is "across the street" from PETCO”
text:
I got this room for $90on Priceline, so the price was right (it was $199 on Expedia). I had clients at PETCO Park that night, and I had a $350 ticket to the game that includs dinner, so I wanted to get to the ballpark early. Well, forget that!!! First of all, GPS tells you to go stright on Park Blvd. to get to hotel. But Park Blvd does not go through to the hotel. The bridge over the railroad tracks is not built yet. So, that, and the fact that most of the raods were closed due to the game made it a NIGHTMARE and took 45 min. longer to get to the property--and it was not a pretty detour downtown to get there!!!! I finally got there with 30 min to shower and get to ballpark. At check in they tell me they are oversold and have to move me.....OK...um....NO. No way. They can reimburse me for my $350 baseball ticket. Well, they miraculously (but kindly) found me a room at the hotel. Had I had to move someplace else downtown, it would have taken FOREVER to get there! So....with that said, getting to the side of the ballpark where will call is was CRAZY. You have to walk clear around therailroad tracks, as the bridge is not done. It looks across the street but IT IS NOT! THe pedicabs are out, but can only take you further away from ballpark! They say they can take you, but they cannot get through! Don't fall for that trap!!! If you want to get to ballpark, allow for at least 30 minutes to walk over!
The construction is a nightmare. I would NOT stay here again till the bridge is completed. If you want some place near ballpark you need to stay on the other side of the railroad tracks--Solamar, Omni, OTHER Hilton, Marriot Gaslamp. This was a horrible experience.

title: “gute Lage”
text:
Das Wellington gefiel mir besonders wegen der zentralen Lage in Manhatten. 
Man ist in nur 5-10 Minuten am Times Square, und auch zum Central Park ist es nicht weiter.
Von innen ist es eher etwas altmodisch und nicht so hip! Auch war unser Zimmer im 2. Stock nicht gerade leise, wenn morgens die Stadt erwacht, aber wer verbringt in New York schon viel Zeit im Hotel?
Die U-Bahn ist direkt nebenan, so hat man einen perfekten Startpunkt zur Erkundung der Stadt!
